Hey @Vardhamansankar, using my test above this produces

```sql
SELECT DISTINCT t.NETWORK_IP,
         t.NETWORK_IP1,
         t.NETWORK_IP2,
         t.NETWORK_IP3,
         t.NETWORK_IP4
FROM 
	(SELECT DISTINCT t1.ipv4digit1 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit2 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit3 || '.0' network_ip, TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit1) network_ip1, TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit2) network_ip2, TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit3) network_ip3, TO_NUMBER ('0') network_ip4, t1.t2_team_id, t1.system_owner_id, t1.system_owner_team_id
	FROM ip_info t1
	WHERE t1.binary_ip >= ''
	        AND t1.binary_ip <= ''
	ORDER BY  network_ip1, network_ip2, network_ip3 ) t
ORDER BY  t.NETWORK_IP1,t.NETWORK_IP2,t.NETWORK_IP3,t.NETWORK_IP4 
```

which is identical and (as far as I can see) correct.

My full code is:
```java
	@Test
	void testStuff() throws Exception {
		CtClass<?> ctClass = Launcher.parseClass(Files.readString(Path.of("/tmp/test/HibernateIpvNetworkIpDao.java")));
		CtBlock<?> body = ctClass.getMethodsByName("searhNetworkIpRangeByTier1").get(0).getBody();
		CtExpression<?> sql = ((CtLocalVariable) body.getStatement(2)).getAssignment();
		StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
		sql.accept(new CtScanner() {
			@Override
			public <T> void visitCtLiteral(CtLiteral<T> literal) {
				result.append(literal.getValue());
			}
		});
		System.out.println(result.toString().strip().replaceAll("\\s{2,}", " "));
	}
```

It would be helpful if you could cut down your processing code (i.e. what my Test above is) to a minimal failing example on your part. The problem sounds quite weird and I am unable to reproduce it.

@Vardhamansankar 
Please read my previous comment again. I can not reproduce the issue and therefore can not suggest a fix â€” as far as I can see *nothing is broken*.

I have provided an example of what I tried to reproduce the issue above, but *my example works*. If you provide a *failing* self contained example â€” as requested by me last month â€” I can have another look at it. Currently I just did not get enough information from you to provide a useful answer.

@I-Al-Istannen I was creating a PR to merge in the passing test that you suggested here. And while that specific test still passes, I _think_ I found another issue that _might_ be related to this? 

Since it wasn't clear to me what "getting the value of `sql`" was meant to represent here (since the incorrect output code originally mentioned also has the `String sql = ...` instead of just the literal value), I thought maybe @Vardhamansankar might be trying to pretty-print the file? 

So, I created a few more tests: one for `Sniper` printer, and a couple for `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter`. In these, I do not make any changes to the original file, and just try to assert that the pretty-printed output seems "correct" (ie, does not the 2 `(` that were at issue here). 

The `Sniper` printer test seems to pass, as does the `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter` test which uses the "optimized parenthesis" flag. However, the one which _does not_ use the `optimized` parenthesis seems to fail because of extra brackets, _one_ of which seems to be near the `where t1.binary_ip >= '")` mentioned in the issue originally  the ones mentioned here (which makes me think it might be a separate issue). I'll post my files that could be used to recreate the issue below, please let me know if I'm doing something unexpected in the failing case! 

### The Test Code
```java
package spoon.test.prettyprinter.testclasses;

public class SampleClassIssue5001 {
    String binaryIpStart = "start";
    String binaryIpEnd = "end";
    String sql = "Select distinct t.NETWORK_IP, t.NETWORK_IP1, t.NETWORK_IP2, t.NETWORK_IP3, t.NETWORK_IP4 " +
            "from (SELECT DISTINCT t1.ipv4digit1 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit2 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit3 " +
            " || '.0' network_ip, " +
            " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit1) network_ip1, " +
            " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit2) network_ip2, " +
            " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit3) network_ip3, " +
            " TO_NUMBER ('0') network_ip4, t1.t2_team_id, " +
            " t1.system_owner_id, t1.system_owner_team_id " +
            " FROM ip_info t1 " +
            " where t1.binary_ip >= '" + binaryIpStart + "' " +
            " and t1.binary_ip <= '" + binaryIpEnd + "' " +
            " ORDER BY network_ip1, network_ip2, network_ip3  " +
            " ) t order by t.NETWORK_IP1,t.NETWORK_IP2,t.NETWORK_IP3,t.NETWORK_IP4 ";
}
```

### The `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter` Tests
This is an addition to the `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinterTest.java` test file. The `testSameOutputWithDefaultSettings` fails, let me know if my setup is not what is expected and that is why I see this failure!
```java
    @Nested
    class LongStringAssignmentInUnchangedFile {
        // This is the string LITERAL that we hope is the pretty-printed value for the "sql" variable.
        // This was obtained from the output produced by the pretty printer at the time, but notice importantly
        // that the parenthesis presented in the original issue (https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/issues/5001) around "from..."
        // and before "binaryIpStart" are not present, which is essentially what the original issue seems to be about.
        private String expectedStringLiteral = "\"Select distinct t.NETWORK_IP, t.NETWORK_IP1, t.NETWORK_IP2, " +
                "t.NETWORK_IP3, t.NETWORK_IP4 \" + \"from (SELECT DISTINCT t1.ipv4digit1 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit2 " +
                "|| '.' || t1.ipv4digit3 \" + \" || '.0' network_ip, \" + \" TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit1) network_ip1, \" + \" TO_NUMBER " +
                "(t1.ipv4digit2) network_ip2, \" + \" TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit3) network_ip3, \" + \" TO_NUMBER ('0') " +
                "network_ip4, t1.t2_team_id, \" + \" t1.system_owner_id, t1.system_owner_team_id \" + \" FROM ip_info t1 \" + \" where " +
                "t1.binary_ip >= '\" + binaryIpStart + \"' \" + \" and t1.binary_ip <= '\" + binaryIpEnd + \"' \" + \" " +
                "ORDER BY network_ip1, network_ip2, network_ip3  \" + \" ) t order by t.NETWORK_IP1,t.NETWORK_IP2,t.NETWORK_IP3,t.NETWORK_IP4 \"";

        @Test
        @GitHubIssue(issueNumber = 5001, fixed = true)
        void testSameOutputWithDefaultSettings() {
            // FAILS
            Launcher launcher = new Launcher();
            launcher.addInputResource("src/test/java/spoon/test/prettyprinter/testclasses/SampleClassIssue5001.java");
            launcher.buildModel();

            // Since there is only one class, there is only one entity returned by "getAll"
            CtCompilationUnit cu = launcher.getFactory().Type().getAll().get(0)
                    .getPosition().getCompilationUnit();

            launcher.getEnvironment().setPrettyPrinterCreator(() -> new DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter(launcher.getEnvironment()));
            PrettyPrinter prettyPrinter = launcher.createPrettyPrinter();
            String output = prettyPrinter.prettyprint(cu);

            assertThat(output, containsString(expectedStringLiteral));
        }

        @Test
        @GitHubIssue(issueNumber = 5001, fixed = true)
        void testSameOutputWithOptimizedParenthesis() {
            // PASSES
            Launcher launcher = createLauncherWithOptimizeParenthesesPrinter();
            launcher.addInputResource("src/test/java/spoon/test/prettyprinter/testclasses/SampleClassIssue5001.java");
            launcher.buildModel();

            // Since there is only one class, there is only one entity returned by "getAll"
            CtCompilationUnit cu = launcher.getFactory().Type().getAll().get(0)
                    .getPosition().getCompilationUnit();

            PrettyPrinter prettyPrinter = launcher.createPrettyPrinter();
            String output = prettyPrinter.prettyprint(cu);

            assertThat(output, containsString(expectedStringLiteral));
        }
    }
```

The failing test produces the following output (with, as we can see, a _ton_ of extra parenthesis):
```java
package spoon.test.prettyprinter.testclasses;
public class SampleClassIssue5001 {
    java.lang.String binaryIpStart = "start";

    java.lang.String binaryIpEnd = "end";

    java.lang.String sql = ((((((((((((((("Select distinct t.NETWORK_IP, t.NETWORK_IP1, t.NETWORK_IP2, t.NETWORK_IP3, t.NETWORK_IP4 " + "from (SELECT DISTINCT t1.ipv4digit1 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit2 || '.' || t1.ipv4digit3 ") + " || '.0' network_ip, ") + " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit1) network_ip1, ") + " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit2) network_ip2, ") + " TO_NUMBER (t1.ipv4digit3) network_ip3, ") + " TO_NUMBER ('0') network_ip4, t1.t2_team_id, ") + " t1.system_owner_id, t1.system_owner_team_id ") + " FROM ip_info t1 ") + " where t1.binary_ip >= '") + binaryIpStart) + "' ") + " and t1.binary_ip <= '") + binaryIpEnd) + "' ") + " ORDER BY network_ip1, network_ip2, network_ip3  ") + " ) t order by t.NETWORK_IP1,t.NETWORK_IP2,t.NETWORK_IP3,t.NETWORK_IP4 ";
}
```
Could that be what the poster was trying to do originally? If that is the case, Not entirely sure what went in to `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter` between 2022 and now to have made this a little bit more worse ðŸ˜… (again, assuming that is what @Vardhamansankar was attempting to do). The 2 PRs that I worked on -- https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/pull/6215, https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/pull/6237 --  should only have impacted Sniper, I _think_ ðŸ¤” 

Let me know if I should merge the PR with the tests I have for now (with the `testSameOutputWithDefaultSettings`'s Github `fixed` annotation-attribute set to `false`). This seems to be Spoon's pretty-printer giving a bit too much love to parenthesis, as we also see in https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/issues/3809

A related question I have: Is there a reason to _not_ always optimize the number of parenthesis? If that fixes this specific issue, then I'm not quite sure I understand why we'd want to be in a situation where `DefaultJavaPrettyPrinter` does not does parenthesis optimization (as not doing so could result in situations like this). So in my understanding there is already a workaround for this bug (using optimized parenthesis printing), but I'm not sure why we don't always do that. 

cc @monperrus @algomaster99

